===Etymology 1===
{{PIE root|en|wedʰ}}
From {{etyl|xno|en}}, from {{etyl|ONF.|en}} {{m|fro|wage}}, a northern variant of {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|gauge}}, {{m|fro|guage}} (whence modern French {{m|fr|gage}}), {{der|en|la|wadium}}, from {{der|en|frk|*waddī}} (cognate with {{cog|ang|wedd}}), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*wadją||pledge}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*wedʰ-||to pledge, redeem a pledge}}. Akin to {{cog|non|veðja||to pledge}}, {{cog|got|𐍅𐌰𐌳𐌹}}. Compare also the doublet {{m|en|gage}}. More at {{m|en|wed}}. Possible contributory etymology from Old English {{m|ang|wǣge}} (meaning "weight," as wages at times have been goods or coin measured on a scale).

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# An amount of money paid to a worker for a [[specify|specified]] quantity of [[work]], usually calculated on an hourly basis and expressed in an amount of money per hour.

